---
import SiteShell from '../layouts/SiteShell.astro';
import { SITE_TITLE, SITE_DESCRIPTION } from '../consts';
---

<SiteShell title={SITE_TITLE} description={SITE_DESCRIPTION}>

  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-inner">
      <span class="eyebrow">Semiotics · Software · AI</span>
      <h1>Software as Language.<br />Reason as Method.</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        Classical philosophy produced methods, not monuments. We apply them to software —
        understanding the <em>telos</em> of every system before touching the code,
        designing interfaces as sign systems that communicate truth,
        building AI that augments rather than supplants human reason.
        The result is software that is clear, purposeful, and genuinely good.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a href="mailto:frontdoor@kecker.co" class="button button-primary">Get in Touch</a>
        <a href="#philosophy" class="text-link">Our philosophy ↓</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Philosophy Pillars -->
  <section class="pillars" id="philosophy">
    <div class="pillars-inner">
      <div class="pillars-header">
        <span class="eyebrow">Our Philosophy</span>
        <h2>Three traditions. One discipline.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="pillars-list">

        <article class="pillar">
          <div class="pillar-mark" aria-hidden="true">I</div>
          <div class="pillar-content">
            <h3>Platonic Form</h3>
            <p class="pillar-tagline">The ideal is the standard.</p>
            <p class="pillar-body">
              Behind every problem lies the Form of what the solution ought to be — clear, true,
              and good. We pursue that Form. The gap between the current and the ideal is not a
              defect to paper over; it is the space in which real craft operates. Every interface,
              API, and system is judged against what it could be, not merely what it is.
            </p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="pillar">
          <div class="pillar-mark" aria-hidden="true">II</div>
          <div class="pillar-content">
            <h3>Aristotelian Logos</h3>
            <p class="pillar-tagline">Reason precedes the code.</p>
            <p class="pillar-body">
              Aristotle taught that reason is the defining capacity of human beings — and that
              good action follows from understanding purpose. We engineer the same way:
              understanding the <em>telos</em> of every system before writing a line of code.
              Software without purpose is machinery. Software with it becomes an instrument of
              human ends.
            </p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="pillar">
          <div class="pillar-mark" aria-hidden="true">III</div>
          <div class="pillar-content">
            <h3>Stoic Virtue</h3>
            <p class="pillar-tagline">Excellence is its own reward.</p>
            <p class="pillar-body">
              The Stoics held that virtue — <em>aretē</em> — is the only unconditional good.
              Everything else is circumstance. We apply this to the craft: shortcuts compound into
              entropy; rigorous work compounds into endurance. We build what lasts not because
              durability is a feature, but because anything less is not worth building.
            </p>
          </div>
        </article>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- What We Build -->
  <section class="services">
    <div class="services-inner">
      <div class="services-header">
        <span class="eyebrow">What We Build</span>
        <h2>Engineering at the intersection of reason and craft.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="services-grid">

        <article class="service-card">
          <span class="eyebrow">01</span>
          <h3>Mobile &amp; Web Engineering</h3>
          <p>
            High-performance applications built with the rigor of logos and the craft of virtue.
            Architectures that remain coherent under growth, interfaces that stay honest under
            pressure. We build for the long run — because coherence is a design choice, not an
            accident.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="service-card">
          <span class="eyebrow">02</span>
          <h3>AI Systems</h3>
          <p>
            Intelligent systems designed with semiotic awareness so they communicate meaning, not
            just outputs. We build AI that augments human capacity rather than circumventing it —
            serving the ends for which it was made, rather than optimizing away from them.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="service-card">
          <span class="eyebrow">03</span>
          <h3>Semiotic UX Design</h3>
          <p>
            Interfaces are sign systems — every affordance, label, and gesture is a sign that
            carries meaning. We design experiences grounded in Peircean semiotics and
            human-centered reasoning. Meaning is not incidental to design; it is the point of it.
          </p>
        </article>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Human Flourishing -->
  <section class="flourishing">
    <div class="flourishing-inner">
      <span class="eyebrow">Eudaimonia</span>
      <blockquote class="pull-quote">
        Software that serves flourishing — for clients, users, employees, and society.
      </blockquote>
      <div class="flourishing-body">
        <p>
          Aristotle called the highest human good <em>eudaimonia</em> — flourishing, not merely
          pleasure or profit. We take this seriously as a design constraint. Software that degrades
          attention, exploits users, or externalizes harm onto the social fabric is, by definition,
          bad software — regardless of its metrics.
        </p>
        <p>
          The obligation runs in every direction: toward clients who need results they can stand
          behind; toward users who deserve systems that respect their agency; toward colleagues
          who do their best work when the work is worth doing; and toward the broader world that
          technology inevitably shapes. None of these obligations are in fundamental conflict.
          Good engineering — reasoning from first principles, guided by virtue — serves all of them.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA -->
  <section class="cta-section">
    <div class="cta-inner">
      <span class="eyebrow">Start a Conversation</span>
      <h2>Ready to build something enduring?</h2>
      <p class="cta-studio">
        We are a focused studio. We take on work that matters — and decline work that doesn't.
        If you're building something worth building, we'd like to hear about it.
      </p>
      <a href="mailto:frontdoor@kecker.co" class="cta-email">frontdoor@kecker.co →</a>
    </div>
  </section>

</SiteShell>
